re that confronts progressives still poses challenges, and the authors propose thoughtful ways to create a new political order by building an inclusive, durable coalition.The collection covers several of the most significant aspects of American political life. Matthew Yglesias, Andrew Bacevich, and Gary Gerstle offer three sober evaluations of the United States in world affairs and the impact of the world on American minds. Next, Todd Gitlin and Andrew Rich examine the struggle to control the messages of politics, through the mainstream media and think tanks, respectively. Ezra Klein, Dean Baker, Karen Kornbluh, and Nelson Lichtenstein each call for major changes in domestic policy grounded in both history and common sense. Finally, Michael Kazin recalls the era when Christian activists were found more often on the left than on the right and argues that a second coming of religious progressivism might be possible today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aPublic Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aBacevich, Andrew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Frans.1 aGerstle, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGitlin, Todd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurenkamp, Menno.1 aKazin, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKazin, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKlein, Ezra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKornbluh, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLichtenstein, Nelson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/